        <h2 id="financial-translation-faqs">Financial Translation FAQs</h2>

        <p>
            <strong
                >Do financial translation services include currency conversion?</strong
            >
        </p>

        <p>
            No, financial translation services typically do not include currency
            conversion. Their primary focus is translating financial documents
            accurately while maintaining the original content and context.
            However, translators may adapt how currencies are displayed (e.g.,
            symbols, abbreviations, or numerical formats) to suit the target
            audience. Currency conversion itself is a separate financial task
            that requires real-time exchange rates and expertise in financial
            calculations, which is outside the scope of translation services.
        </p>
        <p><strong>Do I need a certified translation?</strong></p>
        <p>
            Whether you need a certified financial translation depends on the
            purpose and requirements of the document. Certified financial
            translations are typically required for:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Legal or regulatory filings (e.g., tax returns, audit reports).
            </li>
            <li>
                Visa or immigration processes (e.g., proof of income, bank
                statements).
            </li>
            <li>
                Court submissions (e.g., financial contracts or agreements).
            </li>
            <li>
                International business transactions (e.g., mergers or
                acquisitions).
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            If your document will be submitted to government authorities, legal
            bodies, or financial institutions, it’s best to confirm if
            certification is necessary to ensure compliance.
        </p>

